Reflection Report
This reflection report summarizes the process, methods, outputs, and insights of my data analysis project, which focuses on the relationship between USD time deposit rates of foreign banks in China and US Federal Reserve (Fed) monetary policy.
The core analytical problem addressed in this project is to explore how Fed interest rate policies influence the USD time deposit rates offered by major foreign banks operating in China, including Standard Chartered, HSBC, and Citi. The intended audience and users of this project are investors who are interested in investing in USD time deposits at foreign banks in China. These investors need clear, data-driven insights to make informed decisions about their deposits, and this project aims to provide them with a reliable tool to understand the connection between Fed policies and bank deposit rates.
The dataset used in this project consists of two main parts. First, the USD time deposit rates of different tenures (3-month, 6-month, 1-year, and 2-year) from three major foreign banks in China, which were collected from the official websites of these banks. Second, the Fed benchmark interest rate data, which was obtained from the Wharton Research Data Services (WRDS), ensuring academic reliability and accuracy. This dataset was selected because it directly aligns with the analytical problem—by combining bank-specific deposit rates with Fed policy rates, I could quantify their relationship through correlation analysis, helping investors grasp how Fed decisions might affect their potential returns from USD deposits.
In terms of Python methods, I adopted a systematic workflow to process and analyze the data. First, I used the pandas library to load and organize the raw data, ensuring all data was structured consistently. Then, I performed data cleaning, including standardizing decimal places and removing missing values to ensure data quality. Next, I grouped the data by different deposit tenures for targeted analysis. I used matplotlib to design and plot line charts, defining the x-axis as the year (2018–2026) and the y-axis as interest rates to visualize trends clearly. Additionally, I imported the LinearRegression model from scikit-learn to build a predictive model, calculated Pearson correlation coefficients to determine the strength of the relationship between Fed rates and bank deposit rates, and verified the model’s reliability.
The main outputs and insights of this project are significant for the target users. A key insight is that there is an extremely high positive correlation (coefficient > 0.95) between Fed rates and USD time deposit rates of foreign banks in China, indicating that bank rates closely follow Fed policy adjustments. The reusable predictive model I built can estimate future USD deposit rates based on Fed rate projections, providing investors with practical decision-making support. Moreover, the model is flexible—it can be adapted to other currencies (e.g., euros) by replacing the dataset, allowing users to explore the relationship between deposit rates and other central bank policies.
Despite its strengths, the project has limitations. The bank deposit rate data for 2024–2026 is predictive rather than actual, which may affect the model’s accuracy slightly. Additionally, the model does not consider other factors such as exchange rate fluctuations or promotional rates offered by banks. Possible improvements include expanding the dataset to include more foreign banks, incorporating macroeconomic indicators, and refining the predictive model with more advanced machine learning algorithms.
My personal contribution to this project is designing a practical, user-friendly tool that assists investors in making informed deposit decisions. A key decision I made was optimizing the initial simple comparative model into a reusable predictive tool, enhancing the project’s practical value. Through this task, I learned that AI can effectively assist in improving programming efficiency and code quality. More importantly, I realized the importance of focusing on a project’s reusability and user value—creating a tool that can be adapted to different scenarios is far more impactful than a one-time analysis. This experience has strengthened my data analysis skills and my understanding of translating analytical problems into practical solutions for specific user needs.
